                <div class="collection-headings">

    <div class="collection-heading-group">

                                 
            <h1 class="collection-heading" itemprop="name">
                Alan Rappeport            </h1>
                                        <div class="follow-button-placeholder" style="" data-collection-id="byline.alan-rappeport"></div>
                    
            </div><!-- close collection-heading-group -->

    
    
            <h2 class="collection-subheading" itemprop="about">Alan Rappeport is an economic policy reporter at The New York Times, based in Washington. He covers the Treasury Department and writes about taxes, trade and fiscal matters in the era of President Trump.                        <a class="user-action">More<i class="icon caret-icon"></i></a>
                    </h2>
    
    
</div><!-- close collection-headings -->

            </div>
        </div>
            </header>
            <div class="collection-description">
        <p>Alan Rappeport is an economic policy reporter at The New York Times, based in Washington. He covers the Treasury Department and writes about taxes, trade and fiscal matters in the era of President Trump.</p>
<p>Previously, Mr. Rappeport covered the 2016 presidential campaign. He anchored dozens of debate and election night live chats, chased candidates around the campaign trail and dug into the details of their economic proposals. He was also a member of the team that developed and initiated First Draft, a politics newsletter and news feed that was used to drive campaign coverage.</p>
<p>Before joining the newspaper in 2014, Mr. Rappeport worked for five years as a reporter at The Financial Times in New York. He also worked in London at The Economist, where he was a Marjorie Deane Financial Journalism Foundation fellow.</p>
<p>Mr. Rappeport has master&#8217;s degrees from the London School of Economics and the Columbia University Graduate School of Journalism. He has a bachelor&#8217;s degree from Emory University.</p>    </div>
    
    

    
